/wiki/1984_1._divisjon_(women): The 1984 1. divisjon (women), was the first season of a top-tier women's football league in Norway, and was won by Sprint-Jeløy. The league was contested by 30 teams, divided in three groups of 10 teams.
/wiki/SK_Sprint-Jel%C3%B8y: Sportsklubben Sprint-Jeløy is a Norwegian football club from Jeløya in Moss. The club was founded in 1926 when both Jeløy IF and SK Sprint was formed. The two clubs merged into Sportsklubben Sprint-Jeløy on 11 October 1940.
/wiki/SK_Trondheims-%C3%98rn: SK Trondheims-Ørn is a Norwegian association football club from Trondheim. The club has one of Norway's most famous women's football teams. Starting from 2020 the team will change their name to Rosenborg.
/wiki/Nymark_IL: Nymark Idrettslag is a Norwegian sports club from Årstad, Bergen. It has sections for association football, cycling and athletics.
/wiki/1985_1._divisjon_(women): The 1985 1. divisjon (women), was the second season of a top-tier women's football league in Norway, and was won by Nymark. The league was contested by 30 teams, divided in three groups of 10 teams.
/wiki/Asker_Fotball: Asker Fotball is the football department of Norwegian sports club Asker SK from Asker.
/wiki/1986_1._divisjon_(women): The 1986 1. divisjon (women) was the third season of a top-tier women's football league in Norway, and was won by Sprint-Jeløy. The league was contested by 40 teams, divided in four groups of ten teams. It was the first year that teams from Nord Norge contested in the top league.
/wiki/Klepp_IL: Klepp IL is a Norwegian sports club from the municipality of Klepp. It was founded on 1 October 1919, and has sections for football, handball and gymnastics as well as the less active sections for athletics and orienteering.
/wiki/IK_Grand_Bod%C3%B8: Idrettsklubben Grand Bodø is a Norwegian association football club from Bodø, Nordland. It was founded on 12 April 1917.
/wiki/1987_1._divisjon_(women): The 1987 1. divisjon, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 2 May 1987 and ended on 3 October 1987.
/wiki/1988_1._divisjon_(women): The 1988 1. divisjon season, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 30 April 1988 and ended on 9 October 1988.
/wiki/1989_1._divisjon_(women): The 1989 1. divisjon season, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 29 April 1989 and ended on 1 October 1989.
/wiki/1990_1._divisjon_(women): The 1990 1. divisjon season, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 28 April 1990 and ended on 6 October 1990.
/wiki/1991_1._divisjon_(women): The 1991 1. divisjon season, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 27 April 1991 and ended on 12 October 1991.
/wiki/IL_Sandviken: IL Sandviken is a Norwegian sports club from the neighborhood Sandviken in Bergenhus borough, Bergen. It has sections for football and handball.
/wiki/1992_1._divisjon_(women): The 1992 1. divisjon season, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 25 April 1992 and ended on 17 October 1992.
/wiki/Setskog/H%C3%B8land: LSK Kvinner Fotballklubb is a Norwegian women's football club from Lillestrøm. They currently play in Toppserien, the top division of Norwegian football. The club was founded as Setskog/Høland Fotballklubb on 10 October 1989.
/wiki/1993_1._divisjon_(women): The 1993 1. divisjon season, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 24 April 1993 and ended on 10 October 1993.
/wiki/1994_1._divisjon_(women): The 1994 1. divisjon, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 24 April 1994 and ended on 9 October 1994.
/wiki/1995_1._divisjon_(women): The 1995 1. divisjon, the highest women's football (soccer) league in Norway, began on 22 April 1995 and ended on 14 October 1995.
/wiki/1._divisjon_(women):
The 1. divisjon (Norwegian: 1. divisjon) is the second highest division in women's football in Norway.
It was founded in 1984. Between 1984 and 1995 it served as the first tier. 1. divisjon was replaced as a first tier by the Eliteserien which in turn was replaced by the Toppserien in 2000. It continued as a second tier from 1996 and onwards.
